item.title: How the War began!
item.dc:creator: florian
item.content:encoded: Read through our short introduction to the beginning and ending of the conflicts that lead to our present situation of glorious All-Out-War.   It all began when the Italics declared WAR to the Bold fond-size.  Shortly after this conflict began the Arial joined in on the side of the facist Italics faction and started a backside-stabbing to the  territory of the Bold. Other kinds of smaller and upper Letters were caught in this massive Call to Arms and even some of the traditional New Times Roman were sentenced to fight on the frontlines. Then finally the whole War climaxed with the droppings of some serious Malware, which had been outlawed under general Word- and Warrights. Finally in our present Situation we are still fighting the Fallout that resulted from the destruction of some of our most serious Atom Script Writers. Even though the efforts spend to reach some kind of peace solution, the end of this gruesome war still remains far away. From the Frontlines, War correspondent Florian.

item.title: Cooking for your Colonel! Autumn-Edition
item.dc:creator: florian
item.content:encoded: This week in our Column "Cooking for your Colonel!", how to make a tasty Soup out of a Boot and some Bootsstrap. So last week we made a preview about cooking a nice twelve span Copy Pasta. We from the factory hope you enjoyed this delicious Copy Pasta.This week however, we want to go more into the complex mechanisms of cooking with just the most basic necessities. So we take our Boot and then we take the Straps off it. Dont think your boots are just for yourself. If your Colonel needs something tasty and nutritious, your Bootsstrap is where the magic happens. Just put the boot in a pot, add some long used socks, then add some salt and some ketchup. After letting the flavour soak into the boot for about half an hour, taste a piece of the boot. If its already well done you can take it out,it should now have a crispy but also mellow flavour. Let it rest on the side and begin putting in the Bootsstrap. Carefully slice it into small pieces of string and then put it in the Soup. After 10 minutes of cooking it should be done. As the last step, cut the Boot into easily consumable pieces and add them to the soup. I hope you and your Colonel will enjoy your Meal, Healthcommisionar Florian.
